From: Bruce Ashfield <bruce.ashfield@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] x86/hyperv: disable hypercall-assisted TLB flush

Enabling CONFIG_HYPERV_GUEST is required for Xen to find a usable
platform timer when running as a guest under Hyper-V Generation 2 VMs
(the Hyper-V reference-TSC timer is the only candidate; HPET, ACPI PM
timer and PIT are not exposed).

However, the same config also turns on the Hyper-V assisted TLB flush,
which issues hypercalls through the Hyper-V hypercall page.  On nested
and Generation 2 Hyper-V VMs that hypercall page is not usable -- the
first probe hypercall issued from hypervisor_setup() faults inside
hyperv_flush_tlb() and takes the hypervisor down before dom0 is even
started:

    Xen call trace:
       [<...>] hyperv_flush_tlb
       [<...>] hypervisor_setup

The assisted TLB flush is only a performance optimisation; Xen falls
back to native IPI-based flushing (exactly what it uses on bare metal)
when it is unavailable.  The TLB flush is also the only user of Hyper-V
hypercalls in the tree, so clearing the recommendation means Xen never
executes a Hyper-V hypercall.  The MSR-based reference-TSC timer does
not use hypercalls and is unaffected.

Clear HV_X64_REMOTE_TLB_FLUSH_RECOMMENDED at probe time so the existing
gate in flush_tlb() returns -EOPNOTSUPP and Xen keeps the native path.

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [embedded specific]

Signed-off-by: Bruce Ashfield <bruce.ashfield@gmail.com>
---
 xen/arch/x86/guest/hyperv/hyperv.c | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

--- a/xen/arch/x86/guest/hyperv/hyperv.c
+++ b/xen/arch/x86/guest/hyperv/hyperv.c
@@ -60,6 +60,18 @@ const struct hypervisor_ops *__init hyperv_probe(void)

     ms_hyperv.hints = cpuid_eax(HYPERV_CPUID_ENLIGHTMENT_INFO);

+    /*
+     * The Hyper-V assisted (hypercall-based) TLB flush relies on the
+     * hypercall page being usable.  On nested and Generation 2 Hyper-V
+     * VMs the hypercall page instruction faults, taking down the very
+     * first probe hypercall issued from hypervisor_setup() before dom0
+     * is started.  Clear the recommendation so the flush_tlb() gate
+     * returns -EOPNOTSUPP and Xen falls back to native IPI-based TLB
+     * flushes.  This is the only user of Hyper-V hypercalls; the
+     * MSR-based reference-TSC timer does not use hypercalls.
+     */
+    ms_hyperv.hints &= ~HV_X64_REMOTE_TLB_FLUSH_RECOMMENDED;
+
     if ( ms_hyperv.hints & HV_X64_ENLIGHTENED_VMCS_RECOMMENDED )
         ms_hyperv.nested_features = cpuid_eax(HYPERV_CPUID_NESTED_FEATURES);

